---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { CompareFigure } from "../components/CompareFigure";
import compareData from "../data/baseline-vs-hygiene.json";
import { SITE, u } from "../lib/site";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="The Observatory"
  description="An immutable event log + pure-function views — the working primitive that survived a 4-persona roundtable + 3-angle deep research."
>
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-wide px-6 py-12 lg:px-12 lg:py-20">
    <header class="mx-auto max-w-prose">
      <p class="font-sans text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-ink-500">The working primitive</p>
      <h1 class="mt-4 font-serif text-4xl font-medium leading-[1.1] tracking-[-0.01em] text-ink-900 lg:text-5xl">
        The Observatory
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-5 font-serif text-prose-lg leading-relaxed text-ink-700">
        An <strong>immutable event log</strong> with <strong>importance and confidence as pure functions over the log</strong>. Tier membership is a query concern, not a stored place. The architecture survived a 4-persona roundtable plus 3 dedicated angle-research agents.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="mx-auto mt-14 max-w-prose prose-claim font-serif text-ink-800">
      <h2>Why this shape</h2>
      <p>The proposed two-tier <em>mutable</em> storage architecture is structurally wrong. Tier promotion is a <strong>point of ruin</strong>: if your importance scorer makes a wrong promotion at step 47 of a 200-step run, that error is baked into "consolidated" state and propagates forward. You convert a recoverable error into a structural one.</p>
      <p>The append-only log doesn't have this property. Wrong signals are isolated events, not architectural state. Pure scoring functions over the log mean different scorers can be A/B'd against the same historical events — <strong>deterministically replayable</strong>, debuggable, and amenable to retrospective analysis after new evals or new models ship.</p>
      <p>The "git for agent context" framing is the wrong metaphor. Git models <em>diff intention</em>; an agent log is a <em>fact stream</em>. Don't inherit git's complexity model. The append-only structure is right; the mental model is closer to Datomic than to git.</p>

      <h2>Live comparison</h2>
      <p>The figure below is wired to the JSON output of <code>python -m observatory.eval compare</code>. Re-run the eval, copy the result into <code>site/src/data/baseline-vs-hygiene.json</code>, rebuild — the figure updates.</p>
    </section>

    <div class="mx-auto max-w-prose">
      <CompareFigure data={compareData} client:load />
    </div>

    <section class="mx-auto mt-10 max-w-prose prose-claim font-serif text-ink-800">
      <h2>The shape</h2>
      <pre class="mt-4"><code>{`from observatory import EventLog, view, importance, confidence

log = EventLog()
log.append({"role": "user", "content": "..."})
log.append({"role": "assistant", "content": "..."})
log.append({"role": "tool", "name": "search", "content": "..."})

# Working memory is a derived view, not stored state
working = view(
    log,
    scorer=importance.recency_attention(),  # pure function
    window=4096,
)

# Track retrieval and generation confidence separately
sig = confidence.dissociation(retrieval_score=0.92, generation_score=0.41)
if sig.diverged():
    # The dominant RAG failure mode: overconfidence on wrong context.
    log.append({"role": "verifier", "action": "re-query", "trigger": sig})

# A/B test scorers against the same log — replay-deterministic
alt = view(log, scorer=importance.task_relevance(query="..."), window=4096)
delta = compare(working, alt)`}</code></pre>

      <h2>What ships in v0.1</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><code>EventLog</code> — immutable append-only event log with stable IDs and timestamps</li>
        <li><code>view()</code> — pure function over <code>(log, scorer, window)</code> returning the working set</li>
        <li><code>importance.recency_attention()</code> — composable scorer combining recency and (where available) attention norms</li>
        <li><code>importance.task_relevance(query=...)</code> — query-anchored scorer (importance is context-relative)</li>
        <li><code>confidence.dissociation()</code> — separate retrieval / generation confidence tracking</li>
        <li><code>eval.ruler_extended()</code> — RULER tasks instrumented with hygiene-aware metrics (v0.1 ships a placeholder; real RULER integration in v0.2)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>What's measured</h2>
      <p>The eval harness extends NVIDIA RULER. Two questions in v0.1:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Does importance-weighted active pruning preserve accuracy better than naive truncation on a 5-step agent loop, and at what latency cost? (Carmack's missing number.)</li>
        <li>Does pure-function scoring over an immutable log give the same or better accuracy as a mutable two-tier system, while being deterministically replayable? (The Hickey-Carmack convergence.)</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>What does NOT ship in v0.1</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Real-time attention-pattern hooks into proprietary models (only available where the model exposes them — open weights primarily)</li>
        <li>Branch / merge semantics for divergent agent context (intentionally deferred — single-branch first)</li>
        <li>Cross-provider client SDKs (Python + Anthropic SDK first; OpenAI / Google later)</li>
        <li>A managed service (deliberately not — see the <a href={u("/synthesis")}>angle research</a>)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Install</h2>
      <pre><code>{`pip install observatory      # once published to PyPI
# or:
git clone ${SITE.repo}
cd ai-brain-claims/observatory
pip install -e .
pytest                       # 22 passing tests`}</code></pre>

      <h2>License & contributions</h2>
      <p>MIT. Issues and PRs welcome. The <code>eval/</code> directory accepts new benchmarks. The importance and confidence scorers are designed for community contribution.</p>
    </section>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
